  "local_port": 49214,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My phone is not running 3G but 2G is working fine. 3G is working fine on another phone on the same sim. What can be the problem with my phone?",
  "response": "If your phone is not running 3G but 2G is working fine, and you have confirmed that 3G works on another phone with the same SIM card, there are several potential reasons for the issue:\n\n1. **Network Mode Settings**: Ensure that your phone is set to use 3G. You can check this by going to Settings > Connections > Mobile Networks > Network Mode, and make sure it is set to either 3G or automatically select 3G/4G.\n\n2. **Phone Compatibility**: Some older phones may not support certain 3G frequencies or bands used by your carrier. Verify that your phone is compatible with the 3G network frequencies of your carrier.\n\n3. **APN Settings**: Incorrect Access Point Name (APN) settings can cause issues with connecting to the 3G network. Check that your phone has the correct APN settings for your carrier. This can usually be found in Settings > Connections > Mobile Networks > Access Point Names.\n\n4. **Software/Firmware Issues**: Sometimes, outdated software or firmware can cause connectivity issues. Ensure that your phone's software is up to date.\n\n5. **Network Coverage**: While this seems unlikely as 3G works on another phone with the same SIM, variations in signal reception between different phone models can occur. Verify that you are in an area with adequate 3G coverage.\n\n6. **Sim Slot or Sim Tray Issue**: Although the SIM works in another phone, sometimes there can be issues with the SIM slot or SIM tray in the specific phone. Try reinserting the SIM card or cleaning the SIM card and SIM tray.\n\n7. **Hardware Issues**: If none of the above solutions work, it is possible there could be a hardware defect with your phone\u2019s radio module.\n\nTo troubleshoot:\n1. Make sure your phone is set to use 3G in the network settings.\n2. Confirm that your phone supports 3G frequencies used by your carrier.\n3. Update APN settings.\n4. Update phone software.\n5. Test the SIM card in another slot or another phone temporarily to verify it is not a slot issue.\n6. If the problem persists, consider contacting customer support for your phone\u2019s manufacturer or your carrier for further assistance.",
